               <item n="m_philcomment_old">&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a3.&lt;/b&gt; The first word of the line ought to be restored as &lt;i&gt;yāmoṣne&lt;/i&gt;, translating Skt. &lt;i&gt;kṛte&lt;/i&gt; (37b). At the end of the line one can restore &lt;i&gt;enestai&lt;/i&gt; (as is usual) or &lt;i&gt;enersaṅk&lt;/i&gt; (as in a1) as translation of Skt. &lt;i&gt;rahasi&lt;/i&gt; (37c).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a6.&lt;/b&gt; One may restore the usual match of Skt. &lt;i&gt;rahasi ca kṛte&lt;/i&gt; ‘a deed done in secret’ (here for 38d).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b1.&lt;/b&gt; This line is almost entirely lost.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b2.&lt;/b&gt; The first word ought to be restored as &lt;i&gt;yärpone&lt;/i&gt; which translates Skt. &lt;i&gt;puṇye&lt;/i&gt; (39a). Since the text continues with the translation of pāda 39b, one is led to assume that the (otherwise inattentive) scribe forgot to copy the Sanskrit text.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b4.&lt;/b&gt; The beginning of the line should be restored as &lt;i&gt;akṛtañ ca pāpakam&lt;/i&gt;, which is the end of the pada 40a; again we have a different variant than in the authoritative text: &lt;i&gt;akṛtaṃ ca pāpaṃ&lt;/i&gt; “and not having done a bad deed”.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b5.&lt;/b&gt; The first word ought to be restored as &lt;i&gt;pelaikne&lt;/i&gt; corresponding to Skt. &lt;i&gt;dharmaḥ&lt;/i&gt; (40b).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b6.&lt;/b&gt; The first akṣara of the line belongs to the Sanskrit word &lt;i&gt;dṛḍhayā&lt;/i&gt; ‘solid’ (40d).&lt;/p&gt;</item>
